e from animals, to be used in the production of fur garments or to be tanned for leather. Compare   Skinner  .","Americanized form of German   Scheiner  ."]},{"name":"Shinners","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Seamus.","English and Irish: variant of the Devon name <b>Shinner</b> (itself a variant of   Skinner  ) + excrescent <i>-s</i>. Interchange of <i>sk</i> and <i>sh</i> was an occasional feature of Devon dialect in the 15th century. The name may have been taken from Devon to Ireland in the following centuries."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sarah Skinner was born in 1323, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Skinner. She married Thomas Payne VI. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1323–Deceased":"1323–Surnud","1323–Female":"1323–Surnud","1310–1381":"1310–1381","1315–1380":"1315–1380","1340–1404":"1340–1404","1345–1410":"1345–1410","1347–1398":"1347–1398","1372–1402":"1372–1402","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1404":"1404","1315":"1315","1402":"1402","1347":"1347","1323":"1323","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1398":"1398","1310":"1310","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, Uni